05564nam a22010095i 9780520386976DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203869767 a10.1525/97805203869762doi  a(DE-B1597)626057  a(OCoLC)1338837160  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aTP645b.F47 2022 7aSOC0550002bisacsh04a338.1/7373097281223/eng/202207221 aFischer, Edward F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMaking Better Coffee :bHow Maya Farmers and Third Wave Tastemakers Create Value /cEdward F. Fischer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (306 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Creating Third Wave Values -- t2. Plant Biology, Capitalist Trade, and the Colonial Histories of Coffea arabica -- t3. German Oligarchs, First Wave Coffee, and Guatemala’s Enduring Structures of Inequality -- t4. Austrian Economics and the Quality Turn in Guatemala Coffee -- t5. Maya Farmers and Second Wave Coffee -- t6. Cooperation, Competition, and Cultural Capital in Third Wave Markets -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tImage Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn anthropologist uncovers how ";great coffee"; depends not just on taste, but also on a complex system of values worked out among farmers, roasters, and consumers. What justifies the steep prices commanded by small-batch, high-end Third Wave coffees? Making Better Coffee explores this question, looking at highland coffee farmers in Guatemala and their relationship to the trends that dictate what makes ";great coffee."; Traders stress material conditions of terroir and botany, but just as important are the social, moral, and political values that farmers, roasters, and consumers attach to the beans. In the late nineteenth century, Maya farmers were forced to work on the large plantations that colonized their ancestral lands. The international coffee market shifted in the 1990s, creating demand for high-altitude varietals—plants suited to the mountains where the Maya had been displaced. Edward F. Fisher connects the quest for quality among U.S. tastemakers to the lives and desires of Maya producers, showing how profits are made by artfully combining coffee's material and symbolic attributes. The result is a complex story of terroir and taste, quality and craft, justice and necessity, worth and value.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCoffee industryzGuatemala. 0aCoffeexProcessingzGuatemala. 0aCoffeezGuatemala. 0aMayasxAgriculturezGuatemala. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aanthropology.  aart.  abarista.  abotany.  abusiness.  acafe.  aconsumerism.  acorporation.  aculture.  afarmers.  afood.  agrounds, beans, colombia.  aguatemala.  ahighland.  ahistorical.  alatte.  amaya.  amoral.  aplantations.  apolitical.  aquality.  arestaurant.  aroasters.  ashop.  asmall.  asocial.  ataste.  atastemaker.  aterroir.  athird wave coffee, history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022 Englishz978311099451308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2022z9783110994407oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Califor